1
00:00:29,940 --> 00:00:31,780
- Mrs. Mariann.
- You have the nine and a half?

2
00:00:31,820 --> 00:00:33,256
- Yeah, you're a lucky lady.
- Oh, I'm excited.

3
00:00:33,280 --> 00:00:35,320
Last pair. Let me see
those beautiful feet.

4
00:00:38,280 --> 00:00:39,870
The right foot's all right?

5
00:00:39,950 --> 00:00:41,160
There you go. Get it in there.

6
00:00:42,460 --> 00:00:44,146
- They're too tight.
- It's okay. All right.

7
00:00:44,170 --> 00:00:46,726
- Are these the nine and a half?
- These are the nine and a half, yeah.

8
00:00:46,750 --> 00:00:47,880
Do you have the next size?

9
00:00:47,960 --> 00:00:50,226
No, not in a Kerrybrooke. But
that's why I don't like Kerrybrooke,

10
00:00:50,250 --> 00:00:53,130
because they fit really small.
They're made for dolls or something.

11
00:00:53,220 --> 00:00:55,740
- They're too tight.
- Okay, take 'em off. Don't worry about it.

12
00:00:55,970 --> 00:00:57,470
- You ever try Vitality?
- No.

13
00:00:57,550 --> 00:00:58,720
I'll be right with you.

14
00:00:59,970 --> 00:01:01,600
Excuse me. Sorry.

15
00:01:01,680 --> 00:01:04,520
I bought a pair of shoes here the
other day from him, with the glasses.

16
00:01:04,600 --> 00:01:05,600
- Marty.
- Yeah?

17
00:01:05,690 --> 00:01:07,730
This woman said she bought
a pair of shoes from you.

18
00:01:08,270 --> 00:01:10,650
Oh, yeah. You bought the
brown Mary Janes, right?

19
00:01:10,730 --> 00:01:13,070
Yeah, I did. They're great. I
wore them out of the store.

20
00:01:13,150 --> 00:01:15,200
- Okay.
- So I left my old ones here.

21
00:01:15,280 --> 00:01:16,426
Okay. What did they look like?

22
00:01:16,450 --> 00:01:18,410
They're two-toned pumps, wingtips.

23
00:01:18,490 --> 00:01:20,330
- Lloyd, did you see her shoes?
- No.

24
00:01:20,410 --> 00:01:22,676
Is it possible that you maybe
put them in one of the boxes

25
00:01:22,700 --> 00:01:25,370
of the other shoes that I was
trying on and restocked them?

26
00:01:25,460 --> 00:01:27,500
Okay. All right. Um...

27
00:01:27,580 --> 00:01:29,606
Do you mind if my colleague
helps you out for a second?

28
00:01:29,630 --> 00:01:31,670
Lloyd. Can you help
with Mariann here?

29
00:01:31,750 --> 00:01:32,800
Sure. Sure.

30
00:01:32,880 --> 00:01:34,420
Yeah, we'll check
the basement. Come.

31
00:01:34,510 --> 00:01:35,930
Thank you. Excuse me.

32
00:01:36,010 --> 00:01:37,446
Lloyd's gonna help
you. Get the Vitalities.

33
00:01:37,470 --> 00:01:38,840
Okay. I'll think about the price.

34
00:01:38,930 --> 00:01:40,656
I'll be right with you.
Let me finish up here.

35
00:01:40,680 --> 00:01:41,720
Okay, thank you.

36
00:01:41,810 --> 00:01:42,930
- What?
- Shh.

37
00:01:44,730 --> 00:01:46,060
- Marty.
- Ah, fuck.

38
00:01:46,140 --> 00:01:47,626
I wanna show you
something. Come here.

39
00:01:47,650 --> 00:01:49,560
- What?
- One second. Just get low. Go low.

40
00:01:49,650 --> 00:01:51,020
Why do I have to get low?

41
00:01:53,110 --> 00:01:55,440
- How you doing?
- Marty, look what I got for ya.

42
00:01:55,530 --> 00:01:56,530
What is this?

43
00:01:57,240 --> 00:01:58,240
Check it out.

44
00:01:59,280 --> 00:02:00,490
What am I looking at?

45
00:02:00,570 --> 00:02:01,580
Turn it over.

46
00:02:04,620 --> 00:02:05,960
- Manager?
- Manager.

47
00:02:06,040 --> 00:02:07,210
Come on, Murray.

48
00:02:07,290 --> 00:02:09,290
Whatever you do, just
don't tell Lloyd about this.

49
00:02:09,380 --> 00:02:10,766
Look, I've been
very clear with you.

50
00:02:10,790 --> 00:02:13,920
I'm not trying to be disrespectful. You
built something very commendable here.

51
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:16,300
I don't wanna... I don't
wanna discuss this now.

52
00:02:16,380 --> 00:02:18,130
Stop. Stop. Let me say something.

53
00:02:18,220 --> 00:02:20,680
It's been good for my soul to
see this up close and personal.

54
00:02:20,760 --> 00:02:22,826
- But I'm not a shoe salesman.
- I don't wanna discuss this.

55
00:02:22,850 --> 00:02:25,640
- I'm not a shoe salesman.
- I don't wanna discuss this, okay?

56
00:02:25,720 --> 00:02:27,786
I do wanna discuss it, 'cause when
I'm back from my trip, this is over.

57
00:02:27,810 --> 00:02:28,866
I'm not coming back and doing this.

58
00:02:28,890 --> 00:02:30,996
Speaking of which, can we settle
up now? I gotta buy my plane ticket.

59
00:02:31,020 --> 00:02:32,020
We'll settle at closing.

60
00:02:32,110 --> 00:02:33,376
I wanted to see the
travel agent on my break.

61
00:02:33,400 --> 00:02:35,046
You'll never come back
after your lunch break.

62
00:02:35,070 --> 00:02:36,490
That's what you think of me?

63
00:02:37,190 --> 00:02:39,046
- Yes.
- You think I would go and not come back?

64
00:02:39,070 --> 00:02:40,870
Yes. I said settle
at closing, okay?

65
00:02:40,950 --> 00:02:42,780
- That's it?
- Yeah, that's it. Goodbye.

66
00:02:42,870 --> 00:02:43,990
I love you.

67
00:02:45,290 --> 00:02:46,700
- Come on.
- Wait. Just wait for me.

68
00:02:57,970 --> 00:03:01,680
I was about... I was
about to come to you.

69
00:03:02,260 --> 00:03:03,760
No, Ira's home sick.

70
00:03:03,850 --> 00:03:05,486
- Whoa, whoa, whoa. I can't get sick.
- What?

71
00:03:05,510 --> 00:03:06,640
I got the championships.

72
00:03:06,720 --> 00:03:09,270
No, it's food poisoning.
It's food poisoning.

73
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:34,750
I wish I could hide
you in my luggage.

74
00:03:37,250 --> 00:03:39,340
I wanna come with you so bad.

75
00:05:01,420 --> 00:05:04,680
Backhand. Backhand. Backhand.

76
00:05:04,760 --> 00:05:07,220
{\an8}Forehand. Forehand. Forehand.

77
00:05:07,850 --> 00:05:10,680
{\an8}Backhand. Backhand. Backhand.

78
00:05:11,520 --> 00:05:13,890
{\an8}Forehand. Forehand.

79
00:05:15,060 --> 00:05:16,980
{\an8}Backhand. Backhand.

80
00:05:17,060 --> 00:05:18,230
{\an8}And lob.

81
00:05:19,730 --> 00:05:20,900
{\an8}Forehand.

82
00:05:21,530 --> 00:05:22,650
{\an8}- Marty!
- What!

83
00:05:22,740 --> 00:05:24,820
{\an8}- Phone!
- Tell him I left 20 minutes ago!

84
00:05:24,900 --> 00:05:27,450
{\an8}I'm not your goddamn messenger!
Pick up the goddamn phone!

85
00:05:27,530 --> 00:05:29,620
{\an8}I can't. Wally, take
the white shirt off.

86
00:05:29,700 --> 00:05:31,830
{\an8}I can't follow the white
ball against the white shirt.

87
00:05:31,910 --> 00:05:34,620
{\an8}Stop it. You're a
fucking sun dodger.

88
00:05:34,710 --> 00:05:36,670
{\an8}Oh, yeah? I love you. I love you.

89
00:05:37,620 --> 00:05:38,630
{\an8}Hello?

90
00:05:38,710 --> 00:05:39,920
{\an8}<i>It's Judy.</i>

91
00:05:40,590 --> 00:05:41,840
{\an8}Hi, Judy.

92
00:05:41,920 --> 00:05:43,590
{\an8}<i>Your mother, she's very sick.</i>

93
00:05:43,670 --> 00:05:44,670
{\an8}Okay, really?

94
00:05:44,760 --> 00:05:47,340
{\an8}<i>Yes. She's gray in the face.
She's speaking nonsense.</i>

95
00:05:47,430 --> 00:05:49,140
{\an8}<i>She's asking for you.
You should come home.</i>

96
00:05:49,220 --> 00:05:52,310
{\an8}Sounds really bad. You should
probably call an ambulance.

97
00:05:53,430 --> 00:05:54,640
{\an8}<i>Who's gonna go with her?</i>

98
00:05:54,730 --> 00:05:57,330
{\an8}Uh, I don't know. You should
probably go since you're so invested.

99
00:05:58,100 --> 00:05:59,520
<i>Hold on a minute.</i>

100
00:05:59,610 --> 00:06:00,440
<i>He's not buying it.</i>

101
00:06:00,520 --> 00:06:02,150
<i>Just tell him I stopped breathing!</i>

102
00:06:02,230 --> 00:06:04,940
<i>Absolutely not. That's
ridiculous. I'm not saying that.</i>

103
00:06:05,030 --> 00:06:06,950
Tell him you're taking
me to the hospital.

104
00:06:07,030 --> 00:06:09,160
{\an8}Okay, fine. I'll take her
to the emergency room

105
00:06:09,240 --> 00:06:11,240
{\an8}and sit there and wait
for God knows how long.

106
00:06:11,330 --> 00:06:14,040
{\an8}And you can come here and
give my husband his medicine

107
00:06:14,120 --> 00:06:16,290
{\an8}and massage his
feet all night long.

108
00:06:16,790 --> 00:06:18,250
{\an8}Tell him I passed out.

109
00:06:18,330 --> 00:06:20,960
{\an8}Oh, my God! Your mother,
she just lost consciousness.

110
00:06:21,040 --> 00:06:22,880
{\an8}You've gotta come home now.

111
00:06:24,460 --> 00:06:25,460
{\an8}Hello?

112
00:06:25,550 --> 00:06:27,930
{\an8}Hi. Just give me a second.

113
00:06:30,050 --> 00:06:31,760
<i>I don't know what you
want me to say, Judy.</i>

114
00:06:31,850 --> 00:06:33,220
<i>I'm busy. I'm on my lunch break.</i>

115
00:06:33,310 --> 00:06:36,180
<i>I can hear her whispering. She's
right there standing next to you.</i>

116
00:06:36,270 --> 00:06:38,600
{\an8}<i>- I told you she passed out.
- It's annoying me now.</i>

117
00:06:38,690 --> 00:06:39,690
{\an8}Who are you talking to?

118
00:06:40,310 --> 00:06:42,730
{\an8}Oh. I'm not talking to anybody.

119
00:06:42,820 --> 00:06:45,280
{\an8}Judy's just been tying
up the line for an hour.

120
00:06:45,360 --> 00:06:47,070
{\an8}I got you some broth.

121
00:06:50,030 --> 00:06:51,530
It's ice cold.

122
00:06:51,620 --> 00:06:53,660
Yeah, 'cause the line
was really long at the shop.

123
00:06:53,740 --> 00:06:56,096
Oh, yeah? So that's what
they'll say if I call down and ask?

124
00:06:56,120 --> 00:06:57,840
You don't believe me?
You calling me a liar?

125
00:06:57,870 --> 00:06:59,136
{\an8}Pick up the phone and call them.

126
00:06:59,160 --> 00:07:00,686
{\an8}You're gonna have to
get Judy off the phone first.

127
00:07:00,710 --> 00:07:02,080
Oh, okay.

128
00:07:02,170 --> 00:07:04,040
Hey, Judy, get off the phone.

129
00:07:15,310 --> 00:07:17,980
Okay, this is a normal
IATT approved ball.

130
00:07:18,060 --> 00:07:19,940
Try to follow the white
ball against the white.

131
00:07:21,560 --> 00:07:22,560
Almost impossible, right?

132
00:07:23,110 --> 00:07:24,520
{\an8}I don't even see your eyes moving.

133
00:07:24,610 --> 00:07:26,730
{\an8}If I'm wearing a white
shirt, you can't see the ball.

134
00:07:26,820 --> 00:07:29,500
Now, imagine it with an orange
ball, which no one's ever thought of.

135
00:07:29,530 --> 00:07:31,586
See? You're already following
it way better. Look at his eyes.

136
00:07:31,610 --> 00:07:33,296
- See how his eyes are looking?
- Yeah, I see it.

137
00:07:33,320 --> 00:07:34,620
You're looking more engaged now.

138
00:07:34,700 --> 00:07:36,556
So that's what we wanna do.
Right now in the world of table tennis,

139
00:07:36,580 --> 00:07:39,096
{\an8}you're obliged to wear black,
just so you can follow the white ball.

140
00:07:39,120 --> 00:07:40,870
{\an8}Look at this. That's Ted Bailey.

141
00:07:40,960 --> 00:07:41,960
Who's that?

142
00:07:42,040 --> 00:07:44,056
That's the number one ranked
player in the world right now.

143
00:07:44,080 --> 00:07:45,976
He's the British champion. I've
already beat him, by the way.

144
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:47,050
Now look at this.

145
00:07:47,130 --> 00:07:49,170
That's Jack Kramer,
number one tennis player.

146
00:07:49,260 --> 00:07:51,196
- What's the difference there?
- He's wearing all white.

147
00:07:51,220 --> 00:07:53,010
{\an8}He's in all white. It's beautiful.

148
00:07:53,090 --> 00:07:55,570
{\an8}To me, that's luxury. To me,
that's class. You could sell that.

149
00:07:55,600 --> 00:07:59,020
Marty, a custom ball like that
is gonna cost a lot of money.

150
00:07:59,100 --> 00:08:01,416
Of course it's custom. It's an
original ball for an original guy.

151
00:08:01,440 --> 00:08:03,326
It's the Marty Supreme ball,
not the Marty Normal ball.

152
00:08:03,350 --> 00:08:04,440
But what's it gonna cost?

153
00:08:04,520 --> 00:08:06,730
It doesn't matter the cost.
We can't cheap out on this.

154
00:08:06,820 --> 00:08:08,086
It's gonna be nominal, Mr. Galanis.

155
00:08:08,110 --> 00:08:10,376
{\an8}You always said we gotta spend
money to make money, right?

156
00:08:10,400 --> 00:08:11,650
{\an8}Get me a cup of coffee.

157
00:08:11,740 --> 00:08:13,990
{\an8}No. Get your secretary
to get ya a cup of coffee.

158
00:08:14,070 --> 00:08:15,570
Nancy's busy. Just get me a coffee.

159
00:08:15,660 --> 00:08:17,506
Dad, we're talking like
men about business here.

160
00:08:17,530 --> 00:08:20,160
- I'm not getting ya a cup of coffee.
- Get me the damn coffee!

161
00:08:26,670 --> 00:08:27,540
Marty, you want a coffee?

162
00:08:27,630 --> 00:08:29,390
No, I'm all right. I'm
not drinking caffeine.

163
00:08:33,050 --> 00:08:34,050
Listen.

164
00:08:34,930 --> 00:08:38,430
I appreciate you're
friends with my son.

165
00:08:38,510 --> 00:08:40,640
He's limited.

166
00:08:40,720 --> 00:08:42,480
He's 30 years old.
He's still living at home.

167
00:08:42,560 --> 00:08:44,140
He hasn't done much.

168
00:08:44,230 --> 00:08:47,310
And he doesn't know business.
He doesn't know the costs.

169
00:08:47,400 --> 00:08:49,610
I don't think he's limited,
Mr. Galanis, respectfully.

170
00:08:49,690 --> 00:08:51,530
I mean, look at your
business success.

171
00:08:51,610 --> 00:08:53,626
That's in your DNA, and you
passed that through to Dion.

172
00:08:53,650 --> 00:08:55,700
- It just hasn't been awoken yet.
- I don't know.

173
00:08:55,780 --> 00:08:57,756
{\an8}I wouldn't be here trying
to involve you in something

174
00:08:57,780 --> 00:09:00,410
{\an8}that I didn't fully in
my bones believe in.

175
00:09:00,490 --> 00:09:03,186
I have tremendous respect for your
money. I know it's hard to believe,

176
00:09:03,210 --> 00:09:05,920
but I'm telling you, this game,
it fills stadiums overseas.

177
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:09,016
And it's only a matter of time before it
fills stadiums in the United States too,

178
00:09:09,040 --> 00:09:11,630
before I'm staring at you from
the cover of a Wheaties box.

179
00:09:12,340 --> 00:09:14,260
<i>I don't know nothing
about this business.</i>

180
00:09:14,340 --> 00:09:16,220
<i>No, you don't. That's
why you gotta trust me.</i>

181
00:09:16,300 --> 00:09:19,340
{\an8}<i>This time next week, I'll be the first
American to ever win the British Open.</i>

182
00:09:19,390 --> 00:09:22,230
<i>That'll slide me into the number one
ranking for the World Championship.</i>

183
00:09:22,270 --> 00:09:24,576
Life <i>magazine's gonna cover it.</i>
Look <i>magazine's gonna cover it.</i>

184
00:09:24,600 --> 00:09:28,650
<i>They have to. The editor of</i> Look
<i>magazine, he loves me. They all love me.</i>

185
00:09:28,730 --> 00:09:33,740
{\an8}<i>I'm uniquely positioned to be the face
of the entire sport in the United States.</i>

186
00:09:40,870 --> 00:09:42,080
Lloyd!

187
00:09:51,210 --> 00:09:52,250
I'm closing up.

188
00:09:52,340 --> 00:09:54,300
Yeah, I can see that.
Just here to see my uncle.

189
00:09:54,380 --> 00:09:55,380
He left.

190
00:09:55,470 --> 00:09:58,180
He left? What do you
mean he left? For the day?

191
00:09:59,930 --> 00:10:01,486
He had to take your
mother to the hospital.

192
00:10:01,510 --> 00:10:03,560
For crying out
loud. She's not sick.

193
00:10:03,640 --> 00:10:05,906
Hey, Lloyd, he owes me money.
We were supposed to settle up today.

194
00:10:05,930 --> 00:10:08,190
Well, maybe if you didn't
take that five-hour lunch,

195
00:10:08,270 --> 00:10:10,110
- you would have spoke with him.
- Oh, shut up.

196
00:10:28,290 --> 00:10:29,120
<i>Hello.</i>

197
00:10:29,210 --> 00:10:31,226
You're sounding a lot better,
huh? That happened quick.

198
00:10:31,250 --> 00:10:33,090
<i>I'll live, no thanks to you!</i>

199
00:10:33,170 --> 00:10:35,840
Enough, Mom. Are you
with Murray? Be honest.

200
00:10:36,760 --> 00:10:39,590
<i>No. I think he left
for his trip. Okay?</i>

201
00:10:39,680 --> 00:10:41,220
His trip? What trip?

202
00:10:41,300 --> 00:10:44,600
<i>He's taking Esther to
Kutchers for the weekend.</i>

203
00:10:44,680 --> 00:10:46,770
<i>But he would have
stayed if I asked him to.</i>

204
00:10:46,850 --> 00:10:50,350
You're not sick, Mom. He was supposed
to give me my money for my flight.

205
00:10:50,440 --> 00:10:52,770
<i>Well, I don't know
anything about that, sweetie.</i>

206
00:10:52,860 --> 00:10:54,860
Yes, you do! Why do
you think I'm working here?

207
00:10:54,940 --> 00:10:57,150
I literally only accepted
this job for that.

208
00:10:57,240 --> 00:11:00,070
<i>I have no idea what
you are implying.</i>

209
00:11:00,160 --> 00:11:01,846
- You know what this is?
<i>- What, what is this?</i>

210
00:11:01,870 --> 00:11:04,080
This is sabotage.
You're sabotaging me.

211
00:11:04,160 --> 00:11:06,870
<i>Oh, please. You're
sabotaging your own life.</i>

212
00:11:14,130 --> 00:11:15,590
- What is that?
- What?

213
00:11:16,550 --> 00:11:18,550
Are you seriously
thinking I'm gonna rob you?

214
00:11:18,630 --> 00:11:19,630
Just a reflex.

215
00:11:19,720 --> 00:11:22,236
If I wanted to rob you, you'd be
dead. You'd be in a pool of blood.

216
00:11:22,260 --> 00:11:25,220
I came to grab my suit. You know I
bought this specifically for my trip?

217
00:11:25,310 --> 00:11:27,430
Didn't know you need
a suit to play ping pong.

218
00:11:36,940 --> 00:11:39,440
I just want the $700
that Murray owes me.

219
00:11:39,530 --> 00:11:40,570
Yeah, or what?

220
00:11:40,650 --> 00:11:42,586
- Or I'm gonna shoot you in the leg.
- No you're not.

221
00:11:42,610 --> 00:11:43,490
You sure about that?

222
00:11:43,570 --> 00:11:45,886
You shoot me in the leg, you'll be
spending the next few years in jail.

223
00:11:45,910 --> 00:11:47,310
I'll shoot you in the head instead.

224
00:11:47,370 --> 00:11:48,556
You're not gonna do that either.

225
00:11:48,580 --> 00:11:51,220
Look, Lloyd, I just want what was
promised to me, not a penny more.

226
00:11:51,290 --> 00:11:53,556
I'm gonna be coming home with
ten times that amount in prize money.

227
00:11:53,580 --> 00:11:55,646
So just turn the other cheek,
let me take what I'm owed,

228
00:11:55,670 --> 00:11:57,436
and I'll give you an even
$100 dollars when I get back.

229
00:11:57,460 --> 00:11:59,010
Not interested.

230
00:11:59,090 --> 00:12:01,300
Lloyd, come on. Look at me, please.

231
00:12:01,380 --> 00:12:04,720
We both know you'd love nothing
more than to see my ass get canned.

232
00:12:04,800 --> 00:12:07,116
You're a thousand times more
motivated than me to do this job,

233
00:12:07,140 --> 00:12:08,640
and yet look at this, okay?

234
00:12:08,720 --> 00:12:10,230
Look.

235
00:12:10,310 --> 00:12:13,230
Murray gave that
to me. Flip it over.

236
00:12:13,310 --> 00:12:16,190
Manager. I'm gonna be your boss!

237
00:12:16,270 --> 00:12:18,900
How unfair is that? I could
fire you whenever I want.

238
00:12:18,980 --> 00:12:21,740
I could tell you to sweep the
floor on your hands and knees.

239
00:12:21,820 --> 00:12:23,240
How about that, okay?

240
00:12:24,240 --> 00:12:27,370
Lloyd, I'm actually pointing
a gun at you right now.

241
00:12:27,450 --> 00:12:29,160
I'm actually threatening to use it.

242
00:12:29,240 --> 00:12:32,096
This is a legit robbery like any other.
My fingerprints are all over this thing.

243
00:12:32,120 --> 00:12:33,330
These are facts.

244
00:12:33,420 --> 00:12:35,630
So open the safe, let
me take what I'm owed,

245
00:12:35,710 --> 00:12:38,000
and you can call Murray, tell
him exactly what happened,

246
00:12:38,090 --> 00:12:40,880
get me fired, press charges.
Whatever you want, okay?

247
00:12:43,300 --> 00:12:44,300
Fine.

248
00:12:52,390 --> 00:12:54,440
- Here you go, sir.
- Thank you.

249
00:13:11,660 --> 00:13:13,040
We don't get our own rooms?

250
00:13:15,460 --> 00:13:16,670
It's freezing in here.

251
00:13:17,460 --> 00:13:21,760
I really need you to be
serious now. Eyes on me.

252
00:13:21,840 --> 00:13:23,300
Pakistan, I need you to look at me.

253
00:13:23,380 --> 00:13:25,510
Wait, Japan brought a
team this year? You see that?

254
00:13:25,590 --> 00:13:28,260
Yeah. The Japs sent a team.

255
00:13:28,350 --> 00:13:29,720
What about the travel ban?

256
00:13:29,810 --> 00:13:32,060
- They must have lifted it.
- No more travel ban?

257
00:13:32,140 --> 00:13:35,690
Okay, gentlemen, I want you
to flip your paddles for me now.

258
00:13:35,770 --> 00:13:36,770
Thank you very much.

259
00:13:37,270 --> 00:13:40,480
Here we go. One. Two. Three.

260
00:13:41,020 --> 00:13:42,150
Hold it still.

261
00:13:55,830 --> 00:13:57,500
Match point, Mauser.

262
00:14:19,230 --> 00:14:20,770
Match, Mauser.

263
00:14:24,730 --> 00:14:28,360
You let me get to my forehand too much.
Should've tried to put me in my backhand.

264
00:14:28,450 --> 00:14:29,950
Point, Endo.

265
00:14:50,220 --> 00:14:52,140
Point, Endo.

266
00:14:57,980 --> 00:15:00,440
- What's the score here?
- Nineteen-four.

267
00:15:00,520 --> 00:15:02,730
- The Japanese guy?
- Japanese guy's trashing Bailey.

268
00:15:03,980 --> 00:15:05,860
What's he using?
What's that paddle?

269
00:15:05,940 --> 00:15:08,190
I don't know, mate. No one knows.

270
00:15:10,660 --> 00:15:11,950
It's silent.

271
00:15:12,030 --> 00:15:14,160
- Like a ghost!
- Wow.

272
00:15:16,290 --> 00:15:18,250
Point, Endo.

273
00:15:19,250 --> 00:15:20,960
Match point.

274
00:15:56,200 --> 00:15:58,290
- Great game, Marty.
- Great game.

275
00:15:58,370 --> 00:15:59,790
Match, Mauser.

276
00:16:16,810 --> 00:16:19,770
The winners of the
tournament at Stockholm...

277
00:16:19,850 --> 00:16:22,810
Hey. You're Ram Sethi, right?

278
00:16:22,890 --> 00:16:24,286
Sorry, could you hold for a moment?

279
00:16:24,310 --> 00:16:26,520
- You don't mind?
- No. Can I help you with something?

280
00:16:26,610 --> 00:16:28,836
I was just curious, where are
you staying while you're in town?

281
00:16:28,860 --> 00:16:30,740
What business is it of yours?

282
00:16:30,820 --> 00:16:32,466
I'm just saying, what
hotel are you staying at?

283
00:16:32,490 --> 00:16:34,820
All the IATT representatives
are stationed at the Ritz.

284
00:16:34,910 --> 00:16:37,200
- At the Ritz? Yeah, that's what I heard.
- Yes.

285
00:16:37,280 --> 00:16:39,136
- Do you think that's okay?
- I don't know what you're implying.

286
00:16:39,160 --> 00:16:41,870
- Have you seen where they put me?
- Is it a problem?

287
00:16:41,960 --> 00:16:45,040
Well, with all due
respect, sir, it's a dump.

288
00:16:45,130 --> 00:16:47,630
I'm so sorry it doesn't
meet your high standards.

289
00:16:47,710 --> 00:16:50,670
We offer complimentary housing
to all our players, Mr. Mauser.

290
00:16:50,760 --> 00:16:52,720
So far as I know, you're
the only one to complain.

291
00:16:52,760 --> 00:16:54,906
You're talking to me like I'm
any player off the street, okay?

292
00:16:54,930 --> 00:16:57,100
I need good rest so I
can win the tournament.

293
00:16:57,180 --> 00:16:59,866
You know perfectly well what an American
win will do for the future of the sport.

294
00:16:59,890 --> 00:17:02,980
- I'm good for table tennis, Mr. Sethi.
- Appeal to the USTTA.

295
00:17:03,060 --> 00:17:05,746
There is no USTTA. The USTTA is
two guys and a desk. It doesn't exist.

296
00:17:05,770 --> 00:17:07,286
- Well, that's not my problem.
- It is your problem.

297
00:17:07,310 --> 00:17:09,440
I wanna stay where you're
staying! That's what I need!

298
00:17:09,520 --> 00:17:12,360
I am finding this whole
exchange really offensive.

299
00:17:12,440 --> 00:17:13,820
- You're offended?
- I am offended.

300
00:17:13,900 --> 00:17:17,450
I'm offended! You're making your
star player huddle in a rat's ass!

301
00:17:18,160 --> 00:17:19,620
I'm so sorry for that interruption.

302
00:17:19,700 --> 00:17:22,500
Um, back to Ceylon and Mexico...

303
00:17:22,580 --> 00:17:26,170
- This is a nice hotel. Must cost a mint.
- Yeah, very nice.

304
00:17:26,250 --> 00:17:28,670
The IATT covers accommodations?

305
00:17:28,750 --> 00:17:31,960
- Only for their star players.
- Is that right? How many are there?

306
00:17:32,050 --> 00:17:35,550
Star players? I don't know. I
haven't seen any others, so one.

307
00:17:35,630 --> 00:17:36,906
Any nerves, going into the semis?

308
00:17:36,930 --> 00:17:39,760
Nerves? Against Kletzki?
No. You kidding me?

309
00:17:39,850 --> 00:17:42,100
Well, he's won the tournament
for the last three years.

310
00:17:42,180 --> 00:17:44,890
- He's got quite the reputation.
- I have quite the reputation.

311
00:17:44,980 --> 00:17:48,480
Look, I'm gonna do to Kletzki
what Auschwitz couldn't.

312
00:17:48,560 --> 00:17:50,320
Okay. I'm gonna finish the job.

313
00:17:52,900 --> 00:17:55,700
- Jesus Christ.
- A little strong, mate.

314
00:17:55,780 --> 00:17:57,336
It's all right. I'm
Jewish. I can say that.

315
00:17:57,360 --> 00:17:59,926
In fact, if you think about it,
I'm like Hitler's worst nightmare.

316
00:17:59,950 --> 00:18:01,080
And why's that?

317
00:18:01,160 --> 00:18:02,870
Look at me. I'm here.

318
00:18:02,950 --> 00:18:06,120
I did it, I'm on top. I'm the
ultimate product of Hitler's defeat.

319
00:18:07,080 --> 00:18:09,540
Yeah, write that down. That
was good. Write that down.

320
00:18:09,630 --> 00:18:11,356
- Nice one.
- "Ultimate product of Hitler's defeat."

321
00:18:11,380 --> 00:18:13,646
- I do like that confidence.
- Put that under a picture of me.

322
00:18:13,670 --> 00:18:15,920
- Tell us a bit about your background.
- My background?

323
00:18:20,140 --> 00:18:22,890
No, but seriously... My
mother died in childbirth.

324
00:18:23,010 --> 00:18:25,786
My father was a compulsive loser who
abandoned me when I was two years old.

325
00:18:25,810 --> 00:18:27,536
I got stuck in the New
York City orphanage system,

326
00:18:27,560 --> 00:18:29,440
got shuttled from one
hellhole to the next.

327
00:18:29,520 --> 00:18:31,286
- Naturally, got in trouble with the law.
- Isn't that Kay Stone?

328
00:18:31,310 --> 00:18:32,456
I don't want any
of that to define me.

329
00:18:32,480 --> 00:18:34,650
Excuse me. Excuse me. What?

330
00:18:34,730 --> 00:18:36,650
- It's Kay Stone over there.
- That's her.

331
00:18:36,740 --> 00:18:37,860
Who's that?

332
00:18:37,950 --> 00:18:40,490
Well, you know, the movie
actress. Like, from the 1930s.

333
00:18:40,570 --> 00:18:42,240
<i>- Opportunities.
- Opportunities?</i>

334
00:18:42,330 --> 00:18:43,846
- That was good.
- Yeah, yeah. Great movie.

335
00:18:43,870 --> 00:18:44,740
<i>- Black Box.</i>
- My dad loved her.

336
00:18:44,830 --> 00:18:46,000
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

337
00:18:46,080 --> 00:18:47,620
- She was big?
- She was huge.

338
00:18:47,710 --> 00:18:49,500
Came and went. That's her.

339
00:18:49,580 --> 00:18:52,750
- That's Hollywood, mate.
- Yeah. It's her.

340
00:18:53,590 --> 00:18:54,590
It is indeed.

341
00:18:54,670 --> 00:18:56,210
Something about a lake?

342
00:18:56,300 --> 00:18:58,470
<i>- Shadow Lake.</i>
- Yeah, that was good.

343
00:18:59,930 --> 00:19:02,510
Great legs. Gorgeous,
mate. Gorgeous.

344
00:19:02,600 --> 00:19:03,810
Think I have a chance, lads?

345
00:19:05,100 --> 00:19:06,100
Next question.

346
00:19:15,730 --> 00:19:16,900
<i>Hello?</i>

347
00:19:16,990 --> 00:19:18,610
- Kay?
<i>- Speaking.</i>

348
00:19:18,700 --> 00:19:21,160
Hey, it's Marty Mauser.
I'm in the Royal Suite.

349
00:19:21,240 --> 00:19:23,070
I saw you in the lobby yesterday.

350
00:19:23,160 --> 00:19:23,990
<i>Okay.</i>

351
00:19:24,080 --> 00:19:26,240
Yeah, we made eye contact.
I was being interviewed.

352
00:19:27,450 --> 00:19:28,710
<i>I don't recall.</i>

353
00:19:28,790 --> 00:19:31,460
Well, I'm a huge admirer.

354
00:19:31,540 --> 00:19:33,250
<i>Okay. Can I help
you with something?</i>

355
00:19:33,330 --> 00:19:36,170
Maybe. I just ordered one of
everything off the room service menu.

356
00:19:36,250 --> 00:19:38,460
There's no way I'll be
able to eat it all alone.

357
00:19:38,550 --> 00:19:39,670
<i>Ah.</i>

358
00:19:39,760 --> 00:19:41,400
<i>So you'd like me to
come up to your room?</i>

359
00:19:41,510 --> 00:19:44,260
- Mm-hmm. Yeah.
<i>- Perhaps I should send my husband instead.</i>

360
00:19:44,350 --> 00:19:46,196
Sure. He can come up here,
and I'll come down to you.

361
00:19:46,220 --> 00:19:48,850
<i>- Wonderful. Thank you. Goodbye.</i>
- Wait. I wanna keep talking.

362
00:19:48,930 --> 00:19:50,440
<i>Why is that?</i>

363
00:19:50,520 --> 00:19:52,326
Because I've never talked
to an actual movie star.

364
00:19:52,350 --> 00:19:55,360
<i>Well, now you have. I hope the
experience was all you thought it would be.</i>

365
00:19:55,440 --> 00:19:57,120
You know, I'm something
of a performer too.

366
00:19:57,150 --> 00:19:59,150
<i>- Are you?</i>
- Yeah. You don't believe me?

367
00:19:59,690 --> 00:20:01,030
<i>I</i>...

368
00:20:01,110 --> 00:20:02,740
You... What? What?

369
00:20:03,620 --> 00:20:04,620
<i>You're a performer?</i>

370
00:20:04,700 --> 00:20:07,200
Yeah, I'm a performer. You
got the <i>Daily Mail</i> in front of you?

371
00:20:07,290 --> 00:20:09,330
<i>Uh, I do have it, yes.</i>

372
00:20:09,410 --> 00:20:11,080
Okay. Well, turn to page 12.

373
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:15,000
<i>Uh...</i>

374
00:20:15,670 --> 00:20:16,710
<i>Page 12.</i>

375
00:20:16,790 --> 00:20:18,670
Okay. What am I looking at here?

376
00:20:18,760 --> 00:20:20,510
<i>- Down the middle, in the center.</i>
- Uh.

377
00:20:21,470 --> 00:20:22,470
This is you?

378
00:20:22,550 --> 00:20:25,050
<i>Yeah, "the chosen one."
It's a nice picture, right?</i>

379
00:20:25,140 --> 00:20:26,050
Ping pong?

380
00:20:26,140 --> 00:20:28,326
<i>I play table tennis. I'm here
competing in the British Open.</i>

381
00:20:28,350 --> 00:20:30,230
- How old are you?
<i>- I'm 23.</i>

382
00:20:30,310 --> 00:20:31,640
Twenty-three.

383
00:20:31,730 --> 00:20:32,850
<i>Yeah.</i>

384
00:20:32,940 --> 00:20:35,610
I bet you can't name
one film I've done.

385
00:20:35,690 --> 00:20:36,770
<i>What makes you say that?</i>

386
00:20:36,860 --> 00:20:38,820
Because I stopped acting
before you were born.

387
00:20:38,900 --> 00:20:40,506
<i>- Really? That's really interesting.</i>
- Mm-hmm.

388
00:20:40,530 --> 00:20:43,150
Kay, did you use my
razor to shave your legs?

389
00:20:43,240 --> 00:20:44,320
It's dull. I've cut myself.

390
00:20:44,410 --> 00:20:46,240
- No.
<i>- Who's that? Your husband?</i>

391
00:20:46,320 --> 00:20:48,346
I guess someone must've
snuck in and chopped wood with it.

392
00:20:48,370 --> 00:20:49,830
- I'm on the phone.
<i>- Holy shit.</i>

393
00:20:49,910 --> 00:20:51,580
- With whom?
- Debbie.

394
00:20:51,660 --> 00:20:52,960
- Debbie.
<i>- Debbie?</i>

395
00:20:53,040 --> 00:20:54,170
Tell her to get a life.

396
00:20:54,250 --> 00:20:55,630
<i>- Is he gone?</i>
- Mm-hmm.

397
00:20:55,710 --> 00:20:56,960
<i>Okay.</i>

398
00:20:57,040 --> 00:20:58,776
<i>So, why'd you stop
acting? Let's talk about that.</i>

399
00:20:58,800 --> 00:21:00,000
You know, I really have to go.

400
00:21:00,090 --> 00:21:02,646
<i>You must miss it, don't you? Come
watch me play at Wembley tomorrow.</i>

401
00:21:02,670 --> 00:21:03,680
I... I can't.

402
00:21:03,760 --> 00:21:06,486
<i>Come on. You can watch me dethrone
the number one ranked player in the world.</i>

403
00:21:06,510 --> 00:21:07,510
I'm not available.

404
00:21:07,600 --> 00:21:08,826
<i>Oh, yeah? What you got going on?</i>

405
00:21:08,850 --> 00:21:12,180
Actually, I have a big promotional
event to attend to for my husband.

406
00:21:12,270 --> 00:21:13,730
<i>Oh, okay.</i>

407
00:21:13,810 --> 00:21:15,270
<i>What's he promoting?</i>

408
00:21:15,350 --> 00:21:16,440
Pens.

409
00:21:16,940 --> 00:21:18,520
- <i>Pens? Are you serious?</i>
- Pens.

410
00:21:18,610 --> 00:21:20,320
<i>- Like, writing pens?</i>
- Yes.

411
00:21:20,400 --> 00:21:22,240
<i>What, like, he's a pen salesman?</i>

412
00:21:22,820 --> 00:21:24,450
<i>How can you afford
the suite you're in?</i>

413
00:21:24,530 --> 00:21:26,490
He owns Rockwell Ink.

414
00:21:26,570 --> 00:21:27,700
<i>Oh. Okay. Well...</i>

415
00:21:27,780 --> 00:21:28,870
Yes.

416
00:21:28,950 --> 00:21:31,120
<i>- I know Rockwell Ink.</i>
- I'm sure you do.

417
00:21:31,200 --> 00:21:32,250
<i>Okay.</i>

418
00:21:32,750 --> 00:21:34,330
<i>Well, what's the event?</i>

419
00:21:34,410 --> 00:21:38,710
He's hired Agatha Christie
to sign books at Hatchards.

420
00:21:38,790 --> 00:21:39,790
<i>Ooh.</i>

421
00:21:40,710 --> 00:21:41,920
<i>That sounds really boring.</i>

422
00:21:42,010 --> 00:21:43,050
Okay.

423
00:21:51,470 --> 00:21:54,100
Oh, for God's sake.

424
00:21:55,850 --> 00:21:58,270
- What is it?
<i>- Don't hang up. Just one question.</i>

425
00:21:58,350 --> 00:21:59,996
<i>Does your room face
the street or the courtyard?</i>

426
00:22:00,020 --> 00:22:01,020
I don't know.

427
00:22:01,110 --> 00:22:03,166
<i>Just answer the question. Is it
facing the street or the courtyard?</i>

428
00:22:03,190 --> 00:22:04,440
- The courtyard.
<i>- Okay.</i>

429
00:22:04,530 --> 00:22:07,360
<i>I need you to go to the
window. What floor are you on?</i>

430
00:22:07,450 --> 00:22:08,990
I'm on the third floor, I believe.

431
00:22:09,070 --> 00:22:10,660
<i>Third floor. Okay, perfect.</i>

432
00:22:10,740 --> 00:22:11,740
<i>Look across the street.</i>

433
00:22:11,830 --> 00:22:14,620
<i>You see the open window
with a bowl of fruit on the table?</i>

434
00:22:16,370 --> 00:22:17,580
I do.

435
00:22:17,670 --> 00:22:20,960
<i>Here's what's gonna happen. I'm
gonna make an apple appear in that bowl.</i>

436
00:22:21,040 --> 00:22:24,710
<i>And if I do, you're gonna blow off your
little rendezvous and come watch me play.</i>

437
00:22:24,800 --> 00:22:26,800
No, no, no. I'm not
agreeing to anything, no.

438
00:22:26,880 --> 00:22:29,890
<i>You don't have to agree to anything.
I'm gonna do it anyway. Okay? One...</i>

439
00:22:30,470 --> 00:22:31,470
<i>two...</i>

440
00:22:32,260 --> 00:22:33,260
<i>three.</i>

441
00:22:36,890 --> 00:22:39,310
<i>I'll leave a ticket for
you at the box office.</i>

442
00:23:29,150 --> 00:23:30,910
Point, Mauser.

443
00:23:30,990 --> 00:23:33,160
Twenty to five.

444
00:23:33,240 --> 00:23:36,660
Kletzki trails Mauser
two games to nil.

445
00:23:37,290 --> 00:23:40,370
Game and match point, Mauser.

446
00:23:40,460 --> 00:23:42,146
- Let's have a little fun with this one.
- Okay.

447
00:23:42,170 --> 00:23:43,770
- Have a little fun, all right?
- Gotcha.

448
00:23:44,170 --> 00:23:45,840
Service switches to Kletzki.

449
00:24:16,830 --> 00:24:18,490
Point, Kletzki.

450
00:24:24,040 --> 00:24:26,080
Very well, gentlemen.
Thank you for that. Thank you.

451
00:24:30,840 --> 00:24:33,090
Kletzki serves 6-20.

452
00:24:33,180 --> 00:24:36,680
Mauser leads two games to zero.

453
00:24:36,760 --> 00:24:38,640
Match point again for Mr. Mauser.

454
00:24:38,720 --> 00:24:40,680
Your service again, Kletzki.

455
00:24:45,100 --> 00:24:46,520
Point, Mauser!

456
00:24:48,360 --> 00:24:52,570
Mauser wins the game and
match by 21-6. Three games to nil.

457
00:24:52,650 --> 00:24:57,450
Mauser's on to the finals where
he will face Koto Endo of Japan.

458
00:25:01,700 --> 00:25:03,806
{\an8}Get whatever you want. Don't
even look at the prices, okay?

459
00:25:03,830 --> 00:25:04,830
What are you getting?

460
00:25:04,920 --> 00:25:07,420
I'm gonna get the Beef Wellington
and the caviar tasting plate

461
00:25:07,500 --> 00:25:09,356
because they're the most
expensive items on the menu.

462
00:25:09,380 --> 00:25:12,356
Listen, I would like to keep going
back a little bit about the Globetrotters.

463
00:25:12,380 --> 00:25:13,946
- About the Harlem Globetrotters, again?
- Yes.

464
00:25:13,970 --> 00:25:15,486
- I told you, I'm not interested.
- Why not?

465
00:25:15,510 --> 00:25:16,640
'Cause I don't wanna do it.

466
00:25:16,720 --> 00:25:18,220
It's great money.

467
00:25:18,300 --> 00:25:20,810
And we will travel all over the
world. Have you seen Venice?

468
00:25:20,890 --> 00:25:22,826
I don't wanna be doing
trick shots for a halftime show

469
00:25:22,850 --> 00:25:24,410
while people are
going to the bathroom.

470
00:25:24,480 --> 00:25:25,480
That's beneath me, okay?

471
00:25:25,560 --> 00:25:28,310
- They're treated like royalty.
- Where's the waiter?

472
00:25:28,400 --> 00:25:31,070
- Listen, I know people who have done this.
- Excuse me.

473
00:25:31,150 --> 00:25:32,240
Excuse me.

474
00:25:32,320 --> 00:25:35,240
It's a great opportunity.
We should not miss it.

475
00:25:38,160 --> 00:25:39,410
Marty.

476
00:25:41,540 --> 00:25:43,000
Yes, sir. May I help you, sir?

477
00:25:43,080 --> 00:25:44,000
Hi. Can we order?

478
00:25:44,080 --> 00:25:45,720
Of course, sir. Let
me fetch your waiter.

479
00:25:45,750 --> 00:25:46,750
- Hang on.
- Yes.

480
00:25:47,290 --> 00:25:49,330
Uh, I'll be taking care of
the Rockwell tab tonight.

481
00:25:49,380 --> 00:25:51,920
Put it on my room. The
Royal Suite. Marty Mauser.

482
00:25:52,000 --> 00:25:54,486
- And make sure they know it's me, too.
- I will. Leave it to me, sir.

483
00:25:54,510 --> 00:25:55,946
- Don't take no for an answer.
- I won't.

484
00:25:55,970 --> 00:25:58,970
- Marty Mauser. Royal Suite. Go tell 'em.
- Will do, sir.

485
00:26:01,100 --> 00:26:03,140
Okay. Look at me. Don't
look there. Look at me.

486
00:26:03,220 --> 00:26:04,390
- Who's Rockwell?
- Some bozo.

487
00:26:04,480 --> 00:26:06,480
Look over now. Be subtle
about it. What's he doing?

488
00:26:08,190 --> 00:26:09,980
He hasn't been here before, sir.

489
00:26:10,060 --> 00:26:11,150
He's looking at us.

490
00:26:11,230 --> 00:26:12,230
- Really?
- Yeah.

491
00:26:12,320 --> 00:26:13,626
Okay, keep talking
to me. Be normal.

492
00:26:13,650 --> 00:26:15,150
I want you to reconsider.

493
00:26:15,700 --> 00:26:17,466
We would be a great team.
I wanna do this with you.

494
00:26:17,490 --> 00:26:19,136
Why are you so fixed on
the Harlem Globetrotters?

495
00:26:19,160 --> 00:26:21,200
It's very sad what they do, okay?

496
00:26:21,280 --> 00:26:24,426
Some of the premier athletes on the planet
reduced to acting like circus clowns.

497
00:26:24,450 --> 00:26:25,660
What's he doing now?

498
00:26:25,750 --> 00:26:27,250
Actually, he's coming towards us.

499
00:26:27,330 --> 00:26:29,540
- Just be normal. Act casual.
- Okay, fine. Okay.

500
00:26:34,460 --> 00:26:36,340
Excuse me. Do I know you?

501
00:26:36,420 --> 00:26:37,340
Mm-mmm.

502
00:26:37,430 --> 00:26:38,550
I don't think so.

503
00:26:38,630 --> 00:26:40,850
And you wanna buy dinner
for my entire table tonight?

504
00:26:40,930 --> 00:26:43,100
- Yeah. Is it okay?
- Why?

505
00:26:43,180 --> 00:26:44,930
What do you mean,
why? Do I need a reason?

506
00:26:45,020 --> 00:26:47,270
Let me rephrase that.
What do you want?

507
00:26:47,350 --> 00:26:50,150
No, I don't want anything. It's just
my small way of saying thank you.

508
00:26:50,230 --> 00:26:51,610
- Thank you?
- Yeah.

509
00:26:51,690 --> 00:26:53,270
Thank me for what, specifically?

510
00:26:53,360 --> 00:26:54,360
For all your products.

511
00:26:54,860 --> 00:26:57,150
I mean, where would
we be without pens?

512
00:26:59,490 --> 00:27:01,850
You know, I have many talents,
but the one I'm most proud of

513
00:27:01,910 --> 00:27:04,290
is the ability to smell
bullshit from a mile away...

514
00:27:04,370 --> 00:27:06,950
I'm being completely sincere.

515
00:27:09,580 --> 00:27:12,040
- Where are you from?
- New York. What about you?

516
00:27:12,130 --> 00:27:13,710
New York too. What do you do?

517
00:27:13,790 --> 00:27:15,300
I'm a professional athlete.

518
00:27:15,380 --> 00:27:17,550
- Really? What sport?
- Table tennis.

519
00:27:17,630 --> 00:27:18,880
Table tennis? That's a sport?

520
00:27:18,970 --> 00:27:20,986
Of course it is. I'm here
competing in the British Open.

521
00:27:21,010 --> 00:27:22,156
I'm playing at Wembley tomorrow

522
00:27:22,180 --> 00:27:23,946
in front of a sold-out crowd
in the finals against Japan.

523
00:27:23,970 --> 00:27:25,486
I'm here representing
the United States.

524
00:27:25,510 --> 00:27:27,890
Wait, wait, wait. Japan?
Japan has a team here?

525
00:27:27,980 --> 00:27:30,206
- That's what I just said.
- How'd they get around the travel ban?

526
00:27:30,230 --> 00:27:32,496
Because table tennis is the
fastest growing sport in Asia.

527
00:27:32,520 --> 00:27:34,070
It's huge over there.

528
00:27:34,150 --> 00:27:35,206
Oh, you're gonna like this.

529
00:27:35,230 --> 00:27:37,626
Do you know what they call their
grip? The way they hold their rackets?

530
00:27:37,650 --> 00:27:39,400
- No.
- They call it penholder.

531
00:27:40,660 --> 00:27:41,660
So what?

532
00:27:41,740 --> 00:27:43,030
You can use that.

533
00:27:43,120 --> 00:27:44,120
Use it for what?

534
00:27:44,200 --> 00:27:47,080
For an advertisement or something.
I don't know, you're the business guy.

535
00:27:47,120 --> 00:27:49,460
I'm being rude. This is
my associate, Béla Kletzki.

536
00:27:49,540 --> 00:27:50,540
Nice to meet you, sir.

537
00:27:50,620 --> 00:27:52,830
I assume you're a
table tennis player also?

538
00:27:52,920 --> 00:27:56,210
I am. I am. Actually, I was the
World Champion from '35 to '39.

539
00:27:56,300 --> 00:27:58,020
He was the World
Champion. I beat him today.

540
00:27:58,090 --> 00:27:59,840
He beat me. But he's
much younger than me.

541
00:27:59,920 --> 00:28:01,656
I'm much better than
him, much more talented.

542
00:28:01,680 --> 00:28:05,640
I can't help but notice this tattoo. You
were in one of the camps, weren't you?

543
00:28:05,720 --> 00:28:08,430
Auschwitz-Birkenau.
Yeah. Why do you ask?

544
00:28:08,520 --> 00:28:10,940
My son lost his
life liberating you.

545
00:28:12,940 --> 00:28:14,860
I'm sorry for your loss.

546
00:28:15,440 --> 00:28:17,190
I thought you were
liberated by the Soviets.

547
00:28:17,270 --> 00:28:18,706
- We were.
- It wasn't the Americans.

548
00:28:18,730 --> 00:28:21,490
I didn't mean it literally. He
was serving in the South Pacific.

549
00:28:21,570 --> 00:28:23,700
Well, what happened to him?

550
00:28:23,780 --> 00:28:25,530
What do you mean? He was killed.

551
00:28:26,830 --> 00:28:27,830
You find that funny?

552
00:28:27,910 --> 00:28:31,870
Oh, God. No, I just get
nervous laughter sometimes.

553
00:28:31,960 --> 00:28:33,080
If it's any consolation,

554
00:28:33,170 --> 00:28:35,670
I'll be dropping a third atom
bomb on their heads tomorrow.

555
00:28:35,750 --> 00:28:37,776
Yeah, I'm sure his mother's
gonna get a lot of comfort

556
00:28:37,800 --> 00:28:39,480
that you're playing
ping pong in his honor.

557
00:28:39,510 --> 00:28:41,670
It's not that big of a
deal, but I appreciate it.

558
00:28:41,760 --> 00:28:44,390
Tell him... He used to
diffuse bombs for the Nazis.

559
00:28:44,470 --> 00:28:46,140
Tell him the story
you told me about...

560
00:28:46,220 --> 00:28:47,616
I've got a whole table
of people waiting.

561
00:28:47,640 --> 00:28:49,640
Wait, wait. You're gonna
love this story. Tell him.

562
00:28:50,600 --> 00:28:52,600
- You wanna hear it?
- Not really, but go ahead.

563
00:28:52,690 --> 00:28:54,150
No, tell him. It's beautiful.

564
00:28:54,230 --> 00:28:55,860
Okay, I'll make it quick. So...

565
00:28:55,940 --> 00:28:59,570
when I first got to the
camp, I was put into housing.

566
00:28:59,650 --> 00:29:02,570
Lucky for me, there was an
officer who recognized me.

567
00:29:02,650 --> 00:29:07,280
He had seen me in 1935 at the
World Championships in Prague.

568
00:29:07,370 --> 00:29:11,000
This guy was a real fan.
I mean, a real fan, okay?

569
00:29:11,080 --> 00:29:13,580
You're telling me he let you live
because you played ping pong?

570
00:29:13,660 --> 00:29:15,880
They respected my skills, yeah.

571
00:29:17,250 --> 00:29:21,670
<i>So then, they taught me
how to dismantle SC bombs.</i>

572
00:29:22,170 --> 00:29:23,170
<i>Okay?</i>

573
00:29:23,260 --> 00:29:26,760
<i>Each morning, they would send
me into the woods with the bombs</i>

574
00:29:26,840 --> 00:29:30,180
<i>on the outskirts of the camp where
I could only do damage to myself.</i>

575
00:29:33,520 --> 00:29:35,690
<i>So one time,</i>

576
00:29:35,770 --> 00:29:37,350
<i>I followed a honeybee.</i>

577
00:29:37,440 --> 00:29:38,610
<i>A bee?</i>

578
00:29:38,690 --> 00:29:40,190
<i>A honeybee,</i>

579
00:29:40,270 --> 00:29:42,190
<i>all the way to its hive.</i>

580
00:29:44,820 --> 00:29:46,700
<i>And I smoked all the bees out.</i>

581
00:29:47,910 --> 00:29:50,240
<i>And then broke it open,</i>

582
00:29:50,330 --> 00:29:54,500
and I smeared the honey all over
my chest, my arms, everywhere.

583
00:29:55,040 --> 00:29:56,040
Why?

584
00:29:56,120 --> 00:29:57,750
'Cause later that night,

585
00:29:57,830 --> 00:30:02,510
<i>I let all my bunk mates to lick the
honey off of me for nourishment.</i>

586
00:31:44,320 --> 00:31:45,360
Heads.

587
00:31:47,440 --> 00:31:48,940
- Fuck.
- Endo, choice?

588
00:31:49,030 --> 00:31:50,320
Serve.

589
00:31:50,400 --> 00:31:51,910
I'll go to that side.

590
00:31:58,910 --> 00:32:00,920
- On my right...
- Come on, Marty! Come on!

591
00:32:01,000 --> 00:32:04,590
Marty Mauser of the United
States, ranked second,

592
00:32:04,670 --> 00:32:09,050
versus Koto Endo
of Japan, unranked.

593
00:32:09,130 --> 00:32:12,300
The gentlemen will
battle to the best of five

594
00:32:12,380 --> 00:32:14,680
in games to 21 points.

595
00:32:15,430 --> 00:32:18,640
Each game shall be
won by at least two points.

596
00:32:19,730 --> 00:32:20,850
Good luck, gentlemen.

597
00:32:22,020 --> 00:32:23,440
Quiet, please.

598
00:32:24,860 --> 00:32:26,400
All right!

599
00:32:33,820 --> 00:32:37,790
Point, Endo. One-nil.

600
00:32:42,410 --> 00:32:44,290
Come on, America!

601
00:32:47,290 --> 00:32:51,420
Point, Endo. Two-nil.

602
00:32:53,800 --> 00:32:55,140
All right, Marty!

603
00:32:56,640 --> 00:32:57,640
Come on, Marty!

604
00:33:00,470 --> 00:33:03,480
Point, Endo. Three-nil.

605
00:33:13,200 --> 00:33:17,120
Point, Endo. Four-nil.

606
00:33:22,370 --> 00:33:23,960
Come on, Marty!

607
00:33:30,130 --> 00:33:33,970
Point, Endo. Five-nil.

608
00:33:36,090 --> 00:33:38,390
Service switches to Mauser.

609
00:33:43,560 --> 00:33:46,060
Point, Mauser.

610
00:33:46,150 --> 00:33:48,810
9 serving 19.

611
00:34:05,250 --> 00:34:09,420
Point, Mauser. 10-19.

612
00:34:09,500 --> 00:34:10,500
Okay, Marty!

613
00:34:35,030 --> 00:34:38,990
Point, Endo. 20-10.

614
00:34:40,120 --> 00:34:41,830
Game point.

615
00:34:45,910 --> 00:34:47,210
Go! Serve.

616
00:35:07,890 --> 00:35:11,810
Point, Endo. 21-10.

617
00:35:11,900 --> 00:35:13,570
Game, Endo.

618
00:35:14,530 --> 00:35:18,990
Endo leads two games to zero.

619
00:35:21,450 --> 00:35:23,410
Point, Mauser.

620
00:35:23,490 --> 00:35:25,830
18-16.

621
00:35:40,130 --> 00:35:44,220
Point, Mauser. 17-18.

622
00:35:44,300 --> 00:35:45,390
Go, Marty! Come on!

623
00:35:45,470 --> 00:35:48,140
Service switches to Mauser.

624
00:36:01,740 --> 00:36:03,490
Fuck.

625
00:36:07,490 --> 00:36:11,210
Point, Endo. 17-19.

626
00:36:27,100 --> 00:36:28,100
Oh, fuck.

627
00:36:30,930 --> 00:36:35,730
Point, Endo. 17-20.

628
00:36:35,810 --> 00:36:37,360
And match point.

629
00:36:43,990 --> 00:36:45,950
Quiet, please.

630
00:36:46,660 --> 00:36:49,160
Quiet. Settle down.

631
00:36:49,870 --> 00:36:51,790
Your service, Mauser.

632
00:36:51,870 --> 00:36:53,170
Come on, Marty!

633
00:37:02,050 --> 00:37:03,300
Fuck.

634
00:37:04,760 --> 00:37:06,600
No, bullshit! No!

635
00:37:06,680 --> 00:37:09,260
I want a rematch right now
with a standard-league hard-bat!

636
00:37:09,350 --> 00:37:10,470
That is unacceptable!

637
00:37:10,560 --> 00:37:12,140
What if I had a mechanical arm?

638
00:37:12,230 --> 00:37:14,310
What if I put glue on the
ball? Would that be kosher?

639
00:37:14,350 --> 00:37:17,400
Why, he was getting coached the
entire time! That is unacceptable!

640
00:37:19,480 --> 00:37:22,530
I play real table tennis!
Real table tennis!

641
00:37:23,530 --> 00:37:24,530
Unbelievable.

642
00:37:25,070 --> 00:37:26,070
Unbelievable.

643
00:37:26,160 --> 00:37:28,450
British Open champion from Japan...

644
00:37:28,530 --> 00:37:29,450
Fuck you!

645
00:37:29,530 --> 00:37:30,700
Koto Endo!

646
00:39:15,520 --> 00:39:17,350
Do you have a Milton
Rockwell reservation?

647
00:39:17,430 --> 00:39:20,650
<i>- Excusez-moi?</i>
- Milton Rockwell reservation, please.

648
00:39:20,730 --> 00:39:21,730
Ah, Rockwell?

649
00:39:21,810 --> 00:39:24,150
So, listen, Marty, I wanna
personally thank you

650
00:39:24,230 --> 00:39:26,740
for introducing me to table tennis.

651
00:39:27,320 --> 00:39:29,910
I had no idea what a
phenomenon it was in the Asias.

652
00:39:29,990 --> 00:39:31,796
- Oh, yeah. I know.
- And how big it is in Japan!

653
00:39:31,820 --> 00:39:33,596
That's what I was trying
to tell you. It's huge.

654
00:39:33,620 --> 00:39:36,306
So, I'm thinking of incorporating it
into some of the promotional events

655
00:39:36,330 --> 00:39:38,330
we're gonna be doing
over there in the fall.

656
00:39:38,410 --> 00:39:39,710
How so? What are you thinking?

657
00:39:39,790 --> 00:39:42,420
What I wanna do is
stage an exhibition match

658
00:39:42,540 --> 00:39:46,130
around the time of the World
Championships between you and Endo.

659
00:39:46,210 --> 00:39:48,130
- Mmm.
- I think you'd like that idea.

660
00:39:48,220 --> 00:39:49,470
So I'm gonna make you an offer.

661
00:39:49,550 --> 00:39:51,510
I'll pay you a thousand dollars.

662
00:39:51,590 --> 00:39:54,140
I'll put you up at the
Imperial Hotel in Tokyo.

663
00:39:54,220 --> 00:39:57,076
And if you're leaving from New York,
I'll give you a seat on my private plane,

664
00:39:57,100 --> 00:39:59,286
and you'll fly in luxury
for the first time in your life.

665
00:39:59,310 --> 00:40:00,666
Okay, we can
negotiate my price later.

666
00:40:00,690 --> 00:40:02,416
But this would be before
or after the tournament?

667
00:40:02,440 --> 00:40:04,206
- About a week before the event.
- No, it's gotta be after.

668
00:40:04,230 --> 00:40:06,376
I can't face off against the guy
in public before it actually counts.

669
00:40:06,400 --> 00:40:08,376
Drama is very important to
me. I can't undercut the drama.

670
00:40:08,400 --> 00:40:09,780
Let's not get tied up in minutiae.

671
00:40:09,860 --> 00:40:11,966
I just want to find out if you're
interested in participating.

672
00:40:11,990 --> 00:40:14,596
Oh, yeah. Of course. I'm interested in
any opportunity to show off my talents.

673
00:40:14,620 --> 00:40:17,266
And you don't have to worry either,
'cause this time I'm gonna obliterate him.

674
00:40:17,290 --> 00:40:18,676
It's really the racket
that I'm playing,

675
00:40:18,700 --> 00:40:20,306
but I can assure you,
it's gonna be a victory.

676
00:40:20,330 --> 00:40:22,516
Okay, listen. I need you to
understand what this thing's about.

677
00:40:22,540 --> 00:40:25,040
This is not an official match.

678
00:40:25,130 --> 00:40:26,800
It's not even a real game.

679
00:40:26,880 --> 00:40:30,970
This is purely promotional, to
entertain the Japanese people,

680
00:40:31,050 --> 00:40:33,890
so they buy more of my pens, okay?

681
00:40:33,970 --> 00:40:36,600
You're gonna play a few
games. You're gonna be great.

682
00:40:36,680 --> 00:40:39,560
- But you can't play better than Endo.
- You want me to lose?

683
00:40:41,480 --> 00:40:44,190
Marty, let me show you something.

684
00:40:45,150 --> 00:40:47,440
Biggest magazine in Japan.

685
00:40:47,520 --> 00:40:51,110
You made Endo a national treasure.

686
00:40:51,190 --> 00:40:52,466
- Listen...
- Why are you showing me this?

687
00:40:52,490 --> 00:40:54,176
Do you think this makes me wanna
lose? This makes me wanna win.

688
00:40:54,200 --> 00:40:55,990
Sometimes, when you
lose you're a winner.

689
00:40:56,070 --> 00:40:58,466
- Let me explain. Let me explain.
- I'm ten trillion times better than Endo.

690
00:40:58,490 --> 00:41:00,426
You understand that, right?
It's the racket that beat me.

691
00:41:00,450 --> 00:41:02,136
- He's a mediocre player.
- I couldn't care less.

692
00:41:02,160 --> 00:41:04,290
I don't care about table
tennis. This is theater.

693
00:41:04,370 --> 00:41:06,170
- What are you worried about?
- My reputation.

694
00:41:06,920 --> 00:41:08,476
- Your reputation?
- Yes, my reputation.

695
00:41:08,500 --> 00:41:10,936
I don't wanna throw my reputation
in the trash for you. I'm not doing it.

696
00:41:10,960 --> 00:41:13,550
Aren't you playing in a
vaudeville circus act right now?

697
00:41:13,630 --> 00:41:15,800
What do you mean,
vaudeville? Finish that sentence.

698
00:41:15,890 --> 00:41:18,156
- What are you implying?
- You're the halftime show, Marty.

699
00:41:18,180 --> 00:41:21,060
Of the Harlem Globetrotters!
The finest athletes on the planet.

700
00:41:22,270 --> 00:41:24,730
I've probably played in front
of 80,000 people since January.

701
00:41:24,810 --> 00:41:26,060
That's funny to you?

